(McConnell Center at the University of Louisville via AP)WASHINGTON (AP) — Mitch McConnell’s earliest childhood memory is the day he left the polio treatment center at Warm Springs, Georgia, for the last time.
1 is the fear,” said McConnell in an interview with The Associated Press.
But as more than 16,000 people in the U.S. have died from the coronavirus , the echoes are all too familiar.
The virus particularly struck children, forcing swift closures of schools and playgrounds and, in the sweltering heat, swimming pools.
One memory that does stand clear is the arrival of the polio vaccine, and the relief it brought a weary populace.